amarantin usage
===============

Overview
--------

amarantin builds persistent ROOT sample containers from text lists of input
ROOT files.

The usual workflow is:

  1. Build the software
  2. Generate one or more sample list files
  3. Run mk_sample to create persistent sample ROOT files
  4. Optionally assemble multiple persistent samples into one DatasetIO file
  5. Build persistent EventListIO files from DatasetIO using event-tree selections
  6. Optionally assemble cached signal/background distributions into one ChannelIO file
  7. Optionally run the native xsec fit on that channel
  8. Optionally drive many sample builds through samples-dag.mk

Basic build workflow
--------------------

Configure and build:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
    cmake --build build --parallel

If you need multiple local build trees, keep the extras under the hidden
`.build/` parent:

    tools/configure-build host
    cmake --build .build/host --parallel

The main executable will be:

    build/bin/mk_sample

Basic mk_sample usage
---------------------

General form:

    build/bin/mk_sample [--run-db PATH] --sample sample-key --manifest sample.manifest output.root [origin] [variation] [beam] [polarity]

Legacy transitional form:

    build/bin/mk_sample [--run-db PATH] output.root input.list [origin] [variation] [beam] [polarity]

Example:

    build/bin/mk_sample \
      --sample beam \
      --manifest samples/generated/run1_fhc.beam.sample.manifest \
      build/samples/run1_fhc/beam.root \
      overlay nominal numi fhc

Sample manifest rows are:

    shard sample-list-path

For example:

    beam-s0 samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s0.list
    beam-s1 samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s1.list

If --run-db is not given, SampleIO uses:

  * AMARANTIN_RUN_DB, if it is set
  * otherwise /exp/uboone/data/uboonebeam/beamdb/run.db

Basic mk_dataset usage
----------------------

General form:

    build/bin/mk_dataset [--defs sample.defs] [--campaign name] --run run --beam beam --polarity polarity --manifest dataset.manifest output.root

Legacy transitional form:

    build/bin/mk_dataset [--defs sample.defs] [--manifest dataset.manifest] output.root context sample-key=sample.root [sample-key=sample.root ...]

Example:

    build/bin/mk_dataset \
      --defs samples/generated/run1_fhc.sample.defs \
      --campaign run1_fhc_v08_00_00_82 \
      --run run1 \
      --beam numi \
      --polarity fhc \
      --manifest samples/generated/run1_fhc.dataset.manifest \
      build/datasets/run1_fhc.root

The mk_dataset program reads one or more persistent SampleIO ROOT files and
writes a persistent DatasetIO ROOT file containing keyed samples.

In the native scope mode, the manifest must list already-logical sample ROOT
files and each sample row must be unique.

If --defs is supplied, mk_dataset also stamps workflow-facing sample metadata
from a plain text sample definition file onto each keyed sample. This metadata is then
available later in EventListIO and systematics cache building.

A plain text dataset manifest is one row per logical sample:

    sample sample.root

Example:

    beam build/samples/run1_fhc/beam.root
    dirt build/samples/run1_fhc/dirt.root
    ext build/samples/run1_fhc/ext.root
    signal build/samples/run1_fhc/signal.root

The older context-string path still supports repeated keyed inputs and also
accepts `key=path` rows in `--manifest`.

The plain text format is:

    key variation nominal tag role defname [campaign]

Use `-` for an empty field. Example:

    beam nominal - beam beam numi_overlay_run1_fhc run1_fhc
    beam-sce detector beam sce beam nl_run1_fhc_detvar_sce_goodruns run1_fhc

Basic mk_eventlist usage
------------------------

General form:

    build/bin/mk_eventlist output.root dataset.root [event-tree] [subrun-tree] [selection]

Example:

    build/bin/mk_eventlist \
      build/eventlists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      EventSelectionFilter \
      SubRun \
      "selected != 0"

The mk_eventlist program reads a persistent DatasetIO file, chains the
underlying per-sample job ROOT files, applies a TTreeFormula selection, and
writes a persistent EventListIO file with one selected-event tree per sample.
For non-data samples it resolves `__w_norm__` from the embedded DatasetIO
run/subrun normalization table using the event-tree `run` and `subRun`
branches, resolves `__w_cv__` from the central-value physics weights, and
persists `__w__ = __w_norm__ * __w_cv__` plus `__w2__`.

Basic mk_channel usage
----------------------

General form:

    build/bin/mk_channel [--selection <expr>] [--data-bins <csv>] [--signal-cache <key>] [--background-cache <key>] [--allow-zero-data] output.root input.dists.root signal-sample-key background-sample-key channel-key

or:

    build/bin/mk_channel [--selection <expr>] [--data-bins <csv>] [--manifest <channel.manifest>] [--allow-zero-data] output.root input.dists.root channel-key

Example:

    build/bin/mk_channel \
      --selection "__pass_muon__" \
      --data-bins "12,10,9,7,6,5,4,3,2,1" \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      beam-s0 \
      beam-bkg \
      muon_region

Manifest example:

    build/bin/mk_channel \
      --manifest muon_region.channel.manifest \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      muon_region

The mk_channel program reads cached `DistributionIO` entries, checks that the
channel inputs share common binning plus selection metadata, and writes one
persistent `ChannelIO` object with observed data bins plus per-process
systematic payloads.

In the legacy positional mode, observed bins are still provided explicitly via
`--data-bins` unless `--allow-zero-data` is passed.

In the manifest mode, rows with kind `data` fill the observed bins
automatically.

The plain-text manifest format is one row per channel input:

    process-name kind sample-key [cache-key]

The supported kinds are:

    signal
    background
    data

The current manifest mode expects unique non-data process names.

Basic mk_xsec_fit usage
-----------------------

General form:

    build/bin/mk_xsec_fit [--signal-process <name>] [--output <path>] [--mu-start <value>] [--mu-lower <value>] [--mu-upper <value>] [--allow-zero-data] input.channels.root channel-key

Example:

    build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
      --output build/fits/muon_region.fit.txt \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      muon_region

The mk_xsec_fit program reads one persistent `ChannelIO` object, builds the
default signal-strength problem from the persisted nuisance payloads, profiles
the signal-strength parameter `mu`, and prints or writes a plain-text report.
If every observed bin is zero, the CLI now requires `--allow-zero-data` so an
empty observation is an explicit choice rather than a missing-input accident.

Creating a sample list
----------------------

Use tools/mklist.sh to write a sorted sample list from either:

  * a directory scan
  * an existing list file
  * a SAM definition

Example:

    tools/mklist.sh \
      --dir /pnfs/uboone/scratch/users/nlane/ntuples/v08_00_00_82/numi_fhc_run1/beam/s0/out \
      --pat "nu_selection.root,nu_selection_data.root" \
      --out samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s0.list

The output file is a plain text list, for example:

    /pnfs/uboone/.../file001/nu_selection.root
    /pnfs/uboone/.../file002/nu_selection.root
    /pnfs/uboone/.../file003/nu_selection.root

Detector-variation example from a SAM definition:

    tools/mklist.sh \
      --samdef nl_run1_fhc_detvar_sce_goodruns \
      --out samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-sce.list

Building a single sample by hand
--------------------------------

Once a list exists, build a sample ROOT file directly:

    build/bin/mk_sample \
      --sample beam \
      --manifest samples/generated/run1_fhc.beam.sample.manifest \
      build/samples/run1_fhc/beam.root \
      overlay nominal numi fhc

Reading the arguments from left to right:

  * logical sample key
  * sample manifest path
  * output ROOT file path
  * sample origin
  * variation
  * beam
  * polarity

The older single-list form still works:

    build/bin/mk_sample \
      build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root \
      samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s0.list \
      overlay nominal numi fhc

If you still have a file containing many list paths, pass that bridge input as
`@path` in the legacy form.

Building a persistent dataset by hand
-------------------------------------

Once one or more sample ROOT files already exist, build a DatasetIO file:

    build/bin/mk_dataset \
      --defs samples/generated/run1_fhc.sample.defs \
      --campaign run1_fhc_v08_00_00_82 \
      --run run1 \
      --beam numi \
      --polarity fhc \
      --manifest samples/generated/run1_fhc.dataset.manifest \
      build/datasets/run1_fhc.root

Reading the arguments from left to right:

  * optional sample definition file
  * optional campaign scope
  * dataset run scope
  * dataset beam scope
  * dataset polarity scope
  * dataset manifest path
  * output dataset ROOT file path

The manifest rows are:

  * logical sample key
  * logical sample ROOT path

The older keyed context-string path still works:

    build/bin/mk_dataset \
      build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      run1-numi-fhc \
      beam-s0=build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root \
      beam-s1=build/samples/run1/beam-s1.root

In that compatibility path, the key is the persistent sample name inside the
DatasetIO container and repeated keys are merged.

Building a persistent event list by hand
----------------------------------------

Once a DatasetIO file already exists, build a persistent EventListIO file:

    build/bin/mk_eventlist \
      build/eventlists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      EventSelectionFilter \
      SubRun \
      "selected != 0"

Reading the arguments from left to right:

  * output event-list ROOT file path
  * input dataset ROOT file path
  * source event tree name
  * source subrun tree name
  * TTreeFormula selection expression

The current implementation writes:

    meta/
    samples/<sample-key>/meta/
    samples/<sample-key>/events/selected
    samples/<sample-key>/subruns/SubRun

Building a systematics cache by hand
------------------------------------

The same `mk_eventlist` invocation can also write a `DistributionIO`
systematics cache.

Canonical form:

    build/bin/mk_eventlist \
      --cache-systematics <sample-key> <branch-expr> <nbins> <xmin> <xmax> \
      [--cache-output <path>] \
      [--cache-selection <expr>] \
      [--cache-detvars <csv>] \
      [--cache-fine-nbins <n>] \
      [--cache-genie] \
      [--cache-flux] \
      [--cache-reint] \
      [--cache-no-overwrite] \
      output.eventlist.root \
      input.dataset.root

Representative detector-plus-reweighting example:

    build/bin/mk_eventlist \
      --cache-systematics beam-s0 topological_score 50 0 1 \
      --cache-output build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      --cache-selection "__pass_muon__" \
      --cache-detvars beam-s0-sce,beam-s0-wiremodx \
      --cache-fine-nbins 400 \
      --cache-genie \
      --cache-flux \
      --cache-reint \
      build/eventlists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root

Reading the cache flags from left to right:

  * `--cache-systematics` names the nominal sample and the histogram to cache
  * `--cache-selection` applies the cache-time selection expression
  * `--cache-detvars` names detector-variation samples in the event list
  * `--cache-fine-nbins` chooses the finer on-disk cache binning
  * `--cache-genie`, `--cache-flux`, and `--cache-reint` enable the
    reweighting families on the nominal sample
  * `--cache-output` overrides the default `<eventlist>.dists.root` path
  * `--cache-no-overwrite` preserves existing matching cache entries

Conceptually this builds two systematic lanes and merges them in one
`DistributionIO` payload:

  * detector lane: alternate `EventListIO` samples listed in `--cache-detvars`
  * reweighting lane: alternate weight branches on the nominal sample selected
    by `--cache-genie`, `--cache-flux`, and `--cache-reint`

Building a persistent channel by hand
-------------------------------------

Once a cached DistributionIO file already exists, build a persistent ChannelIO
file:

    build/bin/mk_channel \
      --selection "__pass_muon__" \
      --data-bins "12,10,9,7,6,5,4,3,2,1" \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      beam-s0 \
      beam-bkg \
      muon_region

Reading the arguments from left to right:

  * output channel ROOT file path
  * input cached distribution ROOT file path
  * signal sample key
  * background sample key
  * channel key inside the ChannelIO file

Optional flags let you override the persisted cache keys, process names,
selection text, and observed data bin contents.

To build one final region from many cached processes with automatic observed
data, use a manifest instead:

    build/bin/mk_channel \
      --manifest muon_region.channel.manifest \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      muon_region

Representative manifest:

    signal signal beam-s0
    beam_bkg background beam-bkg
    ext background ext
    dirt background dirt
    obs data beam-data

Reading one manifest row from left to right:

  * process name inside the channel
  * process kind: signal, background, or data
  * cached sample key inside DistributionIO
  * optional explicit cache key; if omitted, mk_channel uses the first cache

Rows with kind `data` are not added as fit processes; they are summed into the
observed channel bins automatically and recorded as observed-data provenance.

Running a native xsec fit by hand
---------------------------------

Once a ChannelIO file already exists, run the native fit:

    build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
      --output build/fits/muon_region.fit.txt \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      muon_region

Reading the arguments from left to right:

  * input channel ROOT file path
  * channel key inside the ChannelIO file

Optional flags let you choose the signal-process name, fit bounds, scan
density, and whether to compute the stat-only interval.

The plain-text fit report includes:

  * convergence flag
  * q_min
  * mu_hat and its total / stat-only intervals
  * observed, signal, background, and total bin predictions
  * fitted nuisance values

Common metadata values
----------------------

Origin values:

  * data
  * external
  * overlay
  * dirt
  * enriched

Variation values:

  * nominal
  * detector

Beam values:

  * numi
  * bnb

Polarity values:

  * fhc
  * rhc

For NuMI samples, polarity should be explicit. For BNB samples, polarity is
not meaningful and is typically left as unknown internally.

Driving many samples with samples-dag.mk
----------------------------------------

The repository includes a simple make-based orchestration layer for sample
list generation and sample ROOT production:

    datasets.mk
    samples-dag.mk

For richer multi-run / multi-variation handling, there is also a flat catalog
workflow under:

    samples/datasets.tsv
    samples/catalog.tsv
    tools/render-sample-catalog.sh

The idea is to treat generated sample ROOT files as persistent build
artifacts.

Current simple datasets.mk example
----------------------------------

The existing file declares datasets and logical samples:

    user := nlane
    release := v08_00_00_82
    pat := nu_selection.root,nu_selection_data.root

    datasets := run1

    root := /pnfs/uboone/scratch/users/$(user)/ntuples/$(release)

    name.run1 := numi_fhc_run1
    base.run1 := $(root)/$(name.run1)
    out.run1 := samplelists/$(name.run1)

    samples.run1 := \
        beam-s0:beam/s0/out

With that configuration, the generated artifacts are:

    samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s0.list
    build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root
    build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root.stamp

Those sample ROOT files can then be assembled into a persistent DatasetIO file
with mk_dataset.

Catalog-driven sample workflow
------------------------------

Render the checked-in flat catalog into generated make and dataset files:

    bash tools/render-sample-catalog.sh

This produces:

    samples/generated/datasets.mk
    samples/generated/run1_fhc.beam.sample.manifest
    samples/generated/run1_fhc.sample.defs
    samples/generated/run1_fhc.dataset.manifest

The generated `datasets.mk` keeps shard-level `.list` generation and also
declares one logical-sample manifest plus one logical `SampleIO` output per
downstream sample key.

Each generated `*.sample.manifest` records explicit shard membership:

    beam-s0 samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s0.list
    beam-s1 samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s1.list

The generated dataset manifest then maps logical keys to already-logical sample
ROOT files such as `beam.root`, `dirt.root`, `ext.root`, `signal.root`, and
detector siblings such as `beam-sce.root`.

Running the sample DAG
----------------------

Build all declared sample lists:

    make -f samples-dag.mk samples-lists

Build all declared sample ROOT files:

    make -f samples-dag.mk samples

Build all declared sample ROOT files from the generated catalog:

    make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk samples

Build all declared logical dataset ROOT files from the generated catalog:

    make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk datasets

Print the sample outputs that would be managed:

    make -f samples-dag.mk print-samples

Print the stamp files:

    make -f samples-dag.mk print-sample-stamps

Remove generated sample outputs and sample lists:

    make -f samples-dag.mk samples-clean

Typical persistent dataset workflow
-----------------------------------

One common sequence is:

    make -f samples-dag.mk samples

    build/bin/mk_dataset \
      build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      run1-numi-fhc \
      beam-s0=build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root

This keeps the per-sample SampleIO ROOT files as persistent intermediate
artifacts and writes a separate DatasetIO file for downstream analysis.

Typical logical-sample dataset workflow
---------------------------------------

When shard-level artifacts should merge into logical keys:

    bash tools/render-sample-catalog.sh

    make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk samples

    make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk datasets

This keeps shard-level `SampleIO` files in the build layer, but exposes
artifact `.list` files in the build layer and writes one logical `SampleIO`
ROOT file per downstream sample key before dataset assembly. Downstream
EventListIO, systematics, plotting, and fitting code then see stable logical
sample keys directly.

Typical event-list workflow
---------------------------

After a DatasetIO file exists, produce a persistent selected-event container:

    build/bin/mk_eventlist \
      build/eventlists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      EventSelectionFilter \
      SubRun \
      "selected != 0"

This keeps DatasetIO as the persistent sample-grouping layer and writes an
EventListIO file that can be loaded in ROOT macros for plotting and printed
summaries.

Typical channel-and-fit workflow
--------------------------------

After a DistributionIO cache already exists, build a channel and fit it:

    build/bin/mk_channel \
      --selection "__pass_muon__" \
      --data-bins "12,10,9,7,6,5,4,3,2,1" \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      build/dists/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      beam-s0 \
      beam-bkg \
      muon_region

    build/bin/mk_xsec_fit \
      --output build/fits/muon_region.fit.txt \
      build/channels/run1-numi-fhc.root \
      muon_region

This keeps the reusable fit inputs in ChannelIO and writes a separate plain
text fit summary as the final downstream product.

How the stamp files work
------------------------

Each generated sample ROOT file has a sibling stamp file:

    build/samples/run1/beam-s0.root.stamp

The stamp file is plain text and records the effective inputs used to decide
whether the sample must be rebuilt.

Example:

    manifest_sha256=...
    list_sha256[samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s0.list]=...
    list_sha256[samplelists/numi_fhc_run1/beam-s1.list]=...
    mk_sample_sha256=...
    origin=overlay
    variation=nominal
    beam=numi
    polarity=fhc
    run_db=
    dataset=run1_fhc
    sample=beam
    manifest=samples/generated/run1_fhc.beam.sample.manifest

In the legacy single-list path, the stamp instead records the source kind /
source ref / source base that produced that one list file.

If the current computed stamp matches the existing one, samples-dag.mk keeps
the existing .root file and does not rerun mk_sample.

This means that changing only one sample list, or changing the mk_sample
binary, only forces regeneration of the affected sample outputs.

Using a non-default run database
--------------------------------

At the command line:

    build/bin/mk_sample \
      --run-db /path/to/run.db \
      --sample beam \
      --manifest samples/generated/run1_fhc.beam.sample.manifest \
      build/samples/run1_fhc/beam.root \
      overlay nominal numi fhc

With samples-dag.mk:

    make -f samples-dag.mk RUN_DB_PATH=/path/to/run.db samples

GPVM workflow
-------------

Typical sequence:

    source ./.container.sh
    source ./.setup.sh
    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
    cmake --build build --parallel
    make -f samples-dag.mk samples

Docker workflow
---------------

Build the image:

    docker build -t amarantin-dev .

Run the repository in the container:

    docker run --rm -it -v "$PWD":/work -w /work amarantin-dev

Then build and run:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
    cmake --build build --parallel
    bash tools/render-sample-catalog.sh
    make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk samples
    make -f samples-dag.mk DATASETS_FILE=samples/generated/datasets.mk datasets
    build/bin/mk_eventlist build/eventlists/run1-numi-fhc.root build/datasets/run1-numi-fhc.root EventSelectionFilter SubRun "selected != 0"

Troubleshooting
---------------

If CMake cannot find ROOT, make sure root-config is on PATH or set ROOT_DIR.

If mk_sample fails on beam normalization, check AMARANTIN_RUN_DB or pass
--run-db explicitly.

If samples-dag.mk does not rebuild when expected, inspect the corresponding
.root.stamp file and compare it against the current list contents and binary.

If mk_dataset fails, check that each keyed sample argument is of the form
key=path or that each manifest row has exactly two fields, that each
referenced sample ROOT file is a valid persistent SampleIO object, and in the
native scope mode that each sample root already carries the matching logical
sample name plus beam / polarity metadata for the requested dataset scope.

If mk_eventlist fails, check that the dataset sample ROOT files actually
contain the named event and subrun trees and that the TTreeFormula selection
expression is valid for the source event tree schema.
